Iran's Health Ministry said on March 16 that there were 1,053 new confirmed cases of pneumonia and 129 new deaths. As of noon local time, Iran confirmed a total of 14,991 cases of new pneumonia, of which 4996 recovered and 853 died.

It was the fifth day in a row that more than 1,000 new cases and more than 100 new one-day deaths have been recorded in Iran since yesterday. The same day, another official died of new crown pneumonia, is responsible for the election, supervision, removal of Iran's Supreme Leader of the Supreme Authority of the Supreme Authority, "Iran expert meeting" a member.

Health Ministry spokesman Jahanpur has urged people not to travel to "hard hit areas" such as the Razavi Khorasan Province capital, Mashhad, according to Iran's Maher News Agency. He stressed that the only way to beat the virus was to stay home and avoid unnecessary travel.

In response to the rapid development of the new coronavirus epidemic, Iran has launched a national mobilization plan on the 5th of this month, aimed at early detection of suspected patients, to ease the pressure on hospital admissions.

Under the plan, 300,000 outbreak detection teams will start in the hard-hit areas, asking individual questions based on people's personal information, and people suspected of being infected will go to medical facilities for testing, those who test positive will be quarantined at home and will receive medication and instructions.

Iran's deputy health minister, Alireza Raeisi, said Thursday that the program had screened 10 million people in four days, 6.5 million in medical centers and 3.7 million online.

Of the 10 million people, 210,000 suffered headaches and fever, 30,000 were taken to medical centers due to severe symptoms, and 1,200 were transferred to hospitals, CCTV news reported, citing the Tasnim News Agency, 900 hospitalized.

Iran's supreme leader, Ali Khamenei, has urged the public to cooperate with the plan. He stressed that the strategy adopted by the government and the health sector must be implemented by all, that the national mobilization plan has a scientific basis and is an effective "extraordinary measure" that can "turn hardships into blessings and threats into opportunities. ".

On the same day, Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif continued to criticize the US for "economic terrorism" against Iran. In a letter to foreign ministers, he said unilateral US sanctions had hampered Iran's efforts to combat the epidemic by affecting drugs, trade in medical equipment and humanitarian aid.

Zarif wrote that while Iran has all the scientific capabilities and health systems needed to combat the epidemic, unilateral U.S. sanctions are hampering Iran's efforts to combat it, according to Xinhua. He urged the international community not to recognize and enforce those illegal sanctions. Zarif's letter was reportedly given to UN Secretary General Gutterres on the same day.

A day earlier, Iran's president, Rohani, had urged other leaders to lift sanctions on Iran after arguing that U.S. sanctions were a serious impediment to the country's efforts to combat the new outbreak of pneumonia.
